Installation

Install covidix from GitHub:

devtools::install_github("MarcLavielle/covidix")

Load the required R packages:

library(covidix)
library(mlxR)
library(reshape2)
library(gridExtra)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
theme_set(theme_bw())

Read the Johns-Hopkins University data

args(rwCovid)
## function (file.out = NULL, data.correction = NULL) 
## NULL
d0 <- rwCovid()

The file correction.csv contains some corrected daily data for some countries (France & Spain) It is then possible to load this corrected data and use it with rwCovid

f <- read.csv(url("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/MarcLavielle/covidix/master/correction.csv"))
head(f)
##   country       date day deaths confirmed
## 1  France 2020-04-02  72    471      2116
## 2  France 2020-04-03  73    588      5233
## 3  France 2020-04-04  74    441      4060
## 4  France 2020-04-05  75    357      2886
## 5  France 2020-04-06  76    595      3116
## 6  France 2020-04-07  77    607      3777
d0 <- rwCovid(data.correction=f)

Write the data

file.data <- "./covid19.csv"
write.csv(d0, file=file.data, quote=F, row.names = F)

Short time mortality forecasting

args(corfit)
## function (data = NULL, country = NULL, shift = NULL, log.scale = FALSE, 
##     variable = c("total", "daily"), n.max = 7, p = 0, point.size = 1.5, 
##     line.size = 0.75, predict = TRUE, interval = TRUE, level = 0.95, 
##     nc.min = 100, nd.min = 5) 
## NULL

The purpose of this function is to find the best time-lag between the series of cumulated cases and the series of cumulated deaths in order to superimpose them as well as possible. Then, a linear model provides an accurate prediction of the number of deaths for the next days.

We select the Italian data:

d.italy <- filterCovid(file.in=file.data, nc.min=1000, nd.min=10, country="Italy")
r=corfit(data=d.italy)
print(r$coeff)
## shift scale 
## 4.000 0.143

Plot the observed and predicted counts (daily and cumulated)

print(r$plot)
## Warning: Removed 8 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

Fit the SIR-type model

args(fitCovid)
## function (data = NULL, country = NULL, nb.day = 14, estim.tau = T, 
##     estim.p0 = T, M = NULL, M.max = 3, d.tau = 6, l.tau = 6, 
##     cw = c(1, 1, 1, 1), dir = ".", K1 = 5, ndt = 5) 
## NULL

The SIR model described here is fitted to the data

Plot the results

args(fitPlot)
## function (country = "France", file = NULL, file.test = NULL, 
##     nb.day = 2, plot.tau = F, plot.pred = T, plot.pred0 = T, 
##     plot.day = T, log.scale = F, level = 0.9, pred.int = F, conf.int = F) 
## NULL

Plot the selected model with the data and the effective reproduction number \(R_{\rm eff}\)

print(fitPlot(file=r$file))
## $pl.R0

## 
## $pl.fit

Add a prediction interval (only the residual error is used here, not the uncertainty on the parameter estimation)

print(fitPlot(file=r$file, pred.int=T)[[2]])
